For whatever reason, it's possible to end up with node associations between issues and versions that no longer exist.

It would be helpful if the integrity checker could find and fix (remove) these associations.  Here's a sample query to detect the problem:

{code:sql}
select count(distinct(sink_node_id)) from nodeassociation where sink_node_entity='Version' and sink_node_id not in (select id from projectversion);
{code}

If that number is non-zero, you have orphaned version associations that can cause problems with JQL searches, browsing by version and with version planning in Greenhopper.

JIRA's "Attachment Settings" page tells you that directory paths can be either 'absolute' or 'relative'. However, when you attempt to change this to a 'relative' path, JIRA will display a warning indicating that it can only accept 'absolute' paths (which is correct behaviour).

Nevertheless, the information is shown on the following JIRA page:
http://<JIRA Server>:<optional port number>/secure/admin/jira/ViewAttachmentSettings.jspa

Needs to be amended so that:
{quote}*Attachment Path:* The absolute or relative path to the directory under which attached files will be stored.{quote}
is changed to either:
{quote}*Attachment Path:* The absolute path to the directory under which attached files will be stored.{quote}
or:
{quote}*Attachment Path:* The path to the directory under which attached files will be stored.{quote}

{{white-space: nowrap;}} was removed from {{#issuetable .assignee, #issuetable .reporter}} in {{global-static.css}} resulting in the assignee / reporter fields wrapping. This change was introduced in JIRA 4.1. Unsure if this was intentional, but it certainly doesn't look good. See attachments for before / after screenshots

Workaround: Add the following to {{global-static.css}}:
{code}
#issuetable .assignee, #issuetable .reporter {
    white-space: nowrap;
}
{code}

